                     <bibref title="http://www.thomasgray.org/resources/biblb.shtml#SmM_1989"
                             linktype="simple">Smith (ed.), <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Index</title> (1989),  83</bibref>
                     <bibref title="http://www.thomasgray.org/resources/biblb.shtml#SuD_1995"
                             linktype="simple">Sutton (ed.), <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Location Register</title> (1995),  414</bibref>
                     <bibref title="" linktype="simple">Ellner, June, "Re: MS 30/44, James Beattie
								papers". E-mail to the editor, 20 December 2006</bibref>
                  </bibliography>
                  <scopecontent>
                     <p>Transcript in the hand of <extref href="http://www.thomasgray.org/resources/glnames.shtml#Beattie, James, 1735-1803"
                                show="replace"
                                linktype="simple">
                           <persname normal="Beattie, James, 1735-1803">James
									Beattie</persname>
                        </extref>, annotated in his hand "<extref href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_William_Peere_Williams,_2nd_Baronet,_of_Clapton"
                                show="new"
                                linktype="simple">
                           <persname normal="Williams, William Peere, Sir, d. 1761">Sir William
										Williams</persname>
                        </extref> (on whose death these lines were written at the
								request of his friend <persname normal="Montagu, Frederick">Mr Frederick
									Montagu</persname>) was killed in the last war. They were
								meant to be inscribed on a monument at <geogname normal="Belle Ile (Morbihan, Brittany, France),          island [7010035]">Bellisle</geogname>; but from some
								difficulties attending the execution of it, this design was not
								executed."
							</p>
